// content/y10/history/islands/x03.js — Year 10 History Topic 3: Elizabethan England (expansion pack: +3 flashcards and +10 questions per island). All original.

FLASHCARDS.push(
  // h10i-03-1 — Elizabeth's Court & Government
  {id:"h10fc-03-1-6", islandId:"h10i-03-1", front:"What was patronage and how did Elizabeth use it to control her court?",
   back:"Patronage was the granting of rewards — titles, offices, land, pensions and monopolies — in return for loyalty and service.\n\nHow Elizabeth used it:\n• All rewards flowed from the Queen alone, so ambitious men had to compete for her favour rather than plot against her.\n• Examples: Robert Dudley was made Earl of Leicester (1564); Christopher Hatton rose to Lord Chancellor; William Cecil became Lord Burghley.\n• She balanced rival factions (e.g. Cecil against Leicester, later Cecil against Essex) so no single group became too powerful.\n\nPatronage turned the nobility's ambition into a tool of royal control.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-1-7", islandId:"h10i-03-1", front:"What was the Essex Rebellion of 1601?",
   back:"Robert Devereux, Earl of Essex, was a young favourite of the elderly Elizabeth.\n\nThe road to rebellion:\n• His campaign against the Irish rebels (1599) failed, and he returned to court without permission.\n• Elizabeth banished him from court and refused to renew his sweet wine monopoly, destroying his income.\n• In February 1601 he marched into London with about 200 followers, hoping the city would rise and help him seize control of the court.\n\nLondoners ignored him; the rising collapsed within a day and Essex was executed for treason.\n\nSignificance: it showed the strains in the patronage system at the end of the reign — but also how secure Elizabeth's hold on the capital remained.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-1-8", islandId:"h10i-03-1", front:"How did Elizabeth manage her Parliaments?",
   back:"Parliament met only when Elizabeth summoned it — just 13 sessions in 44 years — mainly to grant taxation and pass laws.\n\nFlashpoints:\n• Marriage and succession — in the 1560s MPs pressed her to marry or name an heir; she forbade discussion of the topic.\n• Free speech — Peter Wentworth, a Puritan MP, was imprisoned for insisting on Parliament's right to debate anything.\n• Monopolies (1597–1601) — MPs were furious that monopolies granted to courtiers pushed up prices.\n\nIn the 'Golden Speech' (1601) Elizabeth defused the monopolies row by promising reform while declaring her love for her subjects — a masterclass in managing criticism without surrendering power.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},

  // h10i-03-2 — Religion in Elizabethan England
  {id:"h10fc-03-2-6", islandId:"h10i-03-2", front:"What happened in the Revolt of the Northern Earls (1569)?",
   back:"The Earls of Northumberland (Thomas Percy) and Westmorland (Charles Neville) led the only major armed rising of the reign.\n\nAims:\n• Restore Catholicism in England.\n• Marry Mary Queen of Scots to the Duke of Norfolk and place her on the throne.\n\nEvents:\n• Around 4,500–6,000 rebels took Durham, where Catholic Mass was celebrated in the cathedral.\n• The rising collapsed as a royal army approached; the earls fled and hundreds of rebels were executed.\n\nConsequences: it helped provoke the Papal Bull of 1570, hardened Elizabeth's treatment of Catholics and broke the power of the great northern families.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-2-7", islandId:"h10i-03-2", front:"How did Sir Francis Walsingham's intelligence network protect Elizabeth?",
   back:"Walsingham, Secretary of State from 1573, built the most effective spy network in Europe.\n\nMethods:\n• Paid agents and informants in English towns, ports, universities and foreign courts.\n• Interception of letters and use of cipher experts — Thomas Phelippes decoded the letters that destroyed Mary Queen of Scots.\n• Agents provocateurs who infiltrated plots and encouraged conspirators to incriminate themselves.\n• Torture and informers to extract confessions from captured priests.\n\nIn the Babington Plot (1586), Walsingham controlled the 'secret' channel of letters hidden in beer barrels, so every message Mary sent was copied — sealing her fate.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-2-8", islandId:"h10i-03-2", front:"Who were the seminary priests and Jesuits, and how did the government respond?",
   back:"To keep English Catholicism alive after 1559, priests were trained abroad and smuggled into England.\n\n• Seminary priests — trained at the college founded by William Allen at Douai (1568); the first arrived in England in 1574.\n• Jesuits — members of a highly disciplined Catholic order; the mission led by Edmund Campion and Robert Persons began in 1580. Campion was caught, tortured and executed in 1581.\n\nGovernment response:\n• 1585 Act — being a Catholic priest in England became treason; sheltering one was punishable by death.\n• Catholic gentry built 'priest holes' (hiding places, many by the craftsman Nicholas Owen) to conceal visiting priests from searchers.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},

  // h10i-03-3 — Exploration & Elizabethan Culture
  {id:"h10fc-03-3-6", islandId:"h10i-03-3", front:"Who was John Hawkins and why were his voyages significant?",
   back:"John Hawkins (1532–95) was a Plymouth sea captain, trader and later treasurer of the navy.\n\n• In three voyages from 1562 he carried enslaved Africans across the Atlantic and sold them in the Spanish colonies — the beginning of English involvement in the transatlantic slave trade.\n• His third voyage ended in disaster when the Spanish ambushed his fleet at San Juan de Ulua (1568), an event that poisoned Anglo-Spanish relations.\n• As treasurer of the navy from 1577 he promoted the 'race-built' galleon — lower, faster warships armed with long-range guns — which proved decisive against the Armada.\n\nHawkins shows how Elizabethan trade, plunder and naval power were tightly connected.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-3-7", islandId:"h10i-03-3", front:"What developments made Elizabethan voyages of exploration possible?",
   back:"Several improvements came together in the period:\n\n• Navigation instruments — the astrolabe and quadrant allowed sailors to estimate latitude from the sun and stars.\n• Better maps — printed charts spread quickly, and Mercator's projection (1569) made plotting long courses easier.\n• Ship design — galleons with mixed square and triangular (lateen) sails were faster and easier to steer than older vessels.\n• Finance — joint-stock companies let many investors share the cost and risk of a voyage; the East India Company (chartered 1600) was the most famous result.\n\nProfit was the engine: successful voyages could repay investors many times over.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-3-8", islandId:"h10i-03-3", front:"Why was there opposition to the Elizabethan theatre?",
   back:"Not everyone welcomed the playhouses:\n\n• Puritans condemned plays as sinful distractions that encouraged idleness, vanity and disorder.\n• The City of London authorities feared crowds spread plague, attracted pickpockets and tempted apprentices away from work.\n• Because of these restrictions, theatres were built just outside the City's control — in Southwark and Shoreditch.\n• Actors without a noble patron could be treated as vagabonds under the vagrancy laws, which is why companies sought protectors (e.g. the Lord Chamberlain's Men).\n\nRoyal support kept the theatres open: Elizabeth enjoyed plays at court, which shielded the companies from their critics.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},

  // h10i-03-4 — Poverty & the Poor Laws
  {id:"h10fc-03-4-6", islandId:"h10i-03-4", front:"What earlier laws paved the way for the 1601 Poor Law?",
   back:"The 1601 Act consolidated decades of experiments:\n\n• Statute of Artificers (1563) — seven-year apprenticeships for crafts and wages fixed locally by JPs, aiming to keep people in stable work; those refusing to contribute towards poor relief could be punished.\n• Vagabonds Act (1572) — alongside harsh punishments, it made local poor-rate contributions compulsory and required registers of the poor.\n• Act for the Relief of the Poor (1576) — towns had to stock raw materials (wool, flax, iron) so the able-bodied could work, and each county had to build a house of correction for those who refused.\n\nThe pattern: relief for those willing to work, punishment for those who would not.", difficulty:2, category:"definition"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-4-7", islandId:"h10i-03-4", front:"How did individual towns experiment with poor relief before national laws?",
   back:"Town schemes often led the way and influenced Parliament:\n\n• London — the former royal palace of Bridewell became a house of correction where vagrants were set to forced work; hospitals such as St Bartholomew's cared for the sick and Bethlem for the mentally ill.\n• Ipswich (1569) — introduced licences for beggars and opened a hospital that cared for the poor and trained children in useful trades.\n• York — appointed an official to supervise the city's beggars, who had to wear badges.\n• Norwich (1570) — carried out a detailed census of its poor, then separated the 'idle' from the unfortunate and organised work and relief for each group.\n\nThese local successes provided the blueprint for the 1597 and 1601 Acts.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-4-8", islandId:"h10i-03-4", front:"Why were the mid-1590s a crisis decade, and how did the law respond in 1597–98?",
   back:"The crisis:\n• Four disastrous harvests in a row (1594–97) sent food prices soaring; there were food riots, and famine deaths occurred in parts of the north such as Cumbria.\n• War with Spain continued to drain money and men.\n\nThe response (1597–98 Acts):\n• Every parish had to appoint overseers of the poor, who collected the poor rate and organised relief and work.\n• A separate act ordered rogues and vagabonds to be whipped and returned to their parish of birth.\n\nThese measures, confirmed and tidied up in 1601, created the national framework that lasted into the 19th century.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},

  // h10i-03-5 — The Spanish Armada
  {id:"h10fc-03-5-6", islandId:"h10i-03-5", front:"Who commanded the two sides during the Armada campaign of 1588?",
   back:"Spanish command:\n• The fleet was originally to be led by the marquis of Santa Cruz, Spain's most experienced admiral, but he died in February 1588.\n• Philip II replaced him with the Duke of Medina Sidonia — a capable soldier and administrator, but a man with no experience of commanding at sea who even suffered from seasickness. He followed Philip's rigid instructions closely.\n\nEnglish command:\n• Lord Howard of Effingham held overall command of the fleet, based at Plymouth.\n• Sir Francis Drake served as vice-admiral and John Hawkins as rear-admiral, bringing hard-won fighting experience.\n\nThe contrast in experience at sea is one reason historians give for the English success.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-5-7", islandId:"h10i-03-5", front:"How did the two fleets of 1588 compare?",
   back:"Spanish Armada:\n• Around 130 ships, many of them slow armed merchantmen, carrying roughly 19,000 soldiers.\n• Guns were mostly short-range; the plan relied on closing with the enemy, grappling and boarding.\n• Sailed in a disciplined crescent formation, with the strongest warships on the tips protecting the supply and troop ships in the centre.\n\nEnglish fleet:\n• Larger in numbers overall, with a core of about 34 royal warships — Hawkins' 'race-built' galleons, lower and faster than the Spanish ships.\n• Long-range culverins allowed the English to bombard from a distance and refuse to be boarded.\n\nThe mismatch in tactics — boarding versus stand-off gunnery — shaped the whole campaign.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-5-8", islandId:"h10i-03-5", front:"What happened in England after the Armada's defeat?",
   back:"• Tilbury — Elizabeth appeared before her army on 9 August 1588 and declared she had 'the heart and stomach of a king', turning doubts about female rule into propaganda gold.\n• Celebration — a commemorative medal carried the message that God had blown with His winds and scattered the enemy, framing victory as divine favour.\n• A darker side — thousands of English sailors died of typhus and food poisoning in the weeks after the campaign, many still unpaid.\n• The war went on — an English counter-armada under Drake and Norris attacked Portugal in 1589 and failed badly; peace with Spain came only in 1604, after Elizabeth's death.\n\nThe defeat of the Armada was a famous victory, but not the end of the conflict.", difficulty:2, category:"application"},

  // h10i-03-6 — The Historic Environment Site Study
  {id:"h10fc-03-6-6", islandId:"h10i-03-6", front:"Who were Bess of Hardwick and Robert Smythson?",
   back:"• Bess of Hardwick (Elizabeth Shrewsbury, c. 1527–1608) — born into minor Derbyshire gentry, she rose through four marriages, the last to the Earl of Shrewsbury, to become one of the richest women in England. She built the New Hall at Hardwick (1590–97) beside her Old Hall, crowning it with her initials 'ES'.\n• Robert Smythson (c. 1535–1614) — the master mason who designed Hardwick, and earlier worked at Longleat and Wollaton. He is one of the first people in England we can call an architect.\n\nTogether they show two Elizabethan developments: social mobility through marriage and land, and the rise of professionally designed 'prodigy houses' built to impress.", difficulty:2, category:"concept"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-6-7", islandId:"h10i-03-6", front:"How does the interior layout of Hardwick Hall display status?",
   back:"Hardwick is organised vertically — status rises with the floors:\n\n• Ground floor — services and everyday rooms.\n• Middle floor — the family's own living quarters.\n• Top floor — the state rooms: the High Great Chamber, with its painted plaster frieze of the goddess Diana (a compliment to the Virgin Queen), and the long gallery, about 50 metres of space for walking, conversation and displaying portraits and tapestries.\n\nOther signals:\n• Ceilings and windows grow taller floor by floor.\n• Separate stairs and passages kept servants out of sight, reflecting a growing elite desire for privacy.\n\nA visitor literally climbed upwards through the household's hierarchy.", difficulty:3, category:"application"},
  {id:"h10fc-03-6-8", islandId:"h10i-03-6", front:"How do Elizabethan 'prodigy houses' differ from medieval castles, and what does this show?",
   back:"Differences:\n• No moats, battlements, arrow slits or thick defensive walls.\n• Vast outward-facing glass windows instead of small openings.\n• Symmetrical, decorative fronts designed to be admired, often sited prominently (Hardwick stands on a ridge, visible for miles).\n\nWhat this reveals:\n• Internal peace — under strong Tudor government, nobles no longer expected private warfare, so defence could be sacrificed to display.\n• Changing competition — elites now rivalled each other through culture, comfort and royal favour rather than military strength.\n• New technology and taste — gunpowder had made castle walls outdated, while Renaissance ideas reshaped what an impressive house looked like.", difficulty:3, category:"application"}
);

QUESTIONS["h10i-03-1"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-03-1"] || []).concat([
  {q:"How did Elizabeth use patronage to control her nobles?", opts:["She paid every noble a fixed salary from Parliament","She forced all nobles to live permanently at court","She granted titles, offices and monopolies, making ambitious men compete for her favour","She allowed loyal nobles to keep private armies"], c:2,
   e:"All rewards flowed from the Queen alone, so men such as Dudley and Hatton rose by serving her and rivals competed for favour rather than plotting. Private armies were precisely the medieval danger the Tudors had stamped out, not a reward Elizabeth offered."},
  {q:"Which statement best describes Robert Dudley, Earl of Leicester?", opts:["A long-standing favourite of Elizabeth who later commanded English troops in the Netherlands","Elizabeth's Lord Treasurer for forty years","The Spanish ambassador at Elizabeth's court","The admiral who commanded the English fleet in 1588"], c:0,
   e:"Dudley was one of Elizabeth's closest companions, was made Earl of Leicester in 1564 and led the force sent to help the Dutch rebels in 1585. The minister who served for around forty years was William Cecil, not Dudley."},
  {q:"Which of these tasks was carried out by Justices of the Peace?", opts:["Commanding the royal navy","Advising the Queen daily at court","Negotiating treaties with foreign powers","Enforcing laws, fixing local wages and overseeing poor relief in their county"], c:3,
   e:"JPs were unpaid local gentry who kept order in the counties — enforcing statutes, setting wages under the Statute of Artificers and administering poor relief. Daily advice to the Queen came from the Privy Council, which is the tempting confusion here."},
  {q:"What happened in the Essex Rebellion of 1601?", opts:["Essex led a Catholic rising in the north of England","The Earl of Essex marched into London with about 200 followers, found no support and was executed","Essex seized the Tower of London and held it for a month","Essex fled to Spain and entered Philip III's service"], c:1,
   e:"After losing royal favour and his sweet wine monopoly, Essex tried to raise London against Elizabeth's councillors in February 1601; the city stayed loyal, the rising collapsed within a day and he was beheaded. It was a court rebellion in the capital, not a northern religious rising like 1569."},
  {q:"Why did Elizabeth deliver the so-called Golden Speech in 1601?", opts:["To announce her forthcoming marriage","To calm Parliament's anger over monopolies by promising reform while keeping MPs' loyalty","To declare war on Spain","To name James VI of Scotland as her heir"], c:1,
   e:"MPs were furious that monopolies granted to courtiers pushed up prices, so Elizabeth promised to investigate abuses while presenting herself as a queen who loved her people. She never publicly named an heir, so the succession option is the trap."},
  {q:"What was the Great Chain of Being?", opts:["The chain of warning beacons along the south coast","A trade route linking England to Asia","The official order of succession to the throne","The belief that God had fixed everyone's place in a strict social hierarchy"], c:3,
   e:"The Great Chain of Being held that God had ordained a hierarchy running from the monarch down to the poorest beggar, making obedience a religious duty. The beacon chain was a real invasion warning system in 1588, but it has nothing to do with this idea."},
  {q:"Why was the system of patronage so effective at keeping order at court?", opts:["Because every reward depended on the Queen, rivals competed for her favour instead of conspiring against her","Because patronage gave each noble command of an army","Because Parliament approved all court appointments","Because patronage made every courtier equally wealthy"], c:0,
   e:"By keeping every prize in her own gift, Elizabeth converted ambition into loyalty and could balance factions against each other. Patronage deliberately created inequality — the hope of rising higher than rivals was exactly what drove obedience, so the equal-wealth option misreads how it worked."},
  {q:"Why do many historians see the unresolved succession as a growing weakness in the 1590s?", opts:["Because Elizabeth had named too many competing heirs","Because the law barred any Scottish monarch from the English throne","Because courtiers began secretly positioning themselves for the next reign while the Queen refused to name anyone","Because Parliament had already elected a foreign king"], c:2,
   e:"With no named heir, men such as Robert Cecil opened secret correspondence with James VI of Scotland, and faction rivalry like Essex against Cecil grew sharper. Elizabeth's problem was naming nobody at all — the idea that she named too many heirs reverses the truth."},
  {q:"An interpretation claims Elizabeth ruled successfully because she terrified her subjects into obedience. What is the strongest objection to this view?", opts:["Elizabeth never punished anyone during her reign","Her control rested mainly on rewards, propaganda and the careful balancing of factions rather than on terror","Fear played no part at all in Tudor government","Her ministers governed entirely without her"], c:1,
   e:"Elizabeth's everyday control worked through patronage, progresses, portraits and faction management, which is why the court stayed loyal for decades. Claiming she never punished anyone is factually wrong — rebels were executed — so that objection would collapse under cross-examination."},
  {q:"Which factor best explains why the Essex Rebellion failed so quickly?", opts:["Spanish troops arrived in time to defend the Queen","Essex's grievances were not genuine","Essex's followers were heavily outnumbered in open battle","Londoners refused to rise, and the Crown's grip on the capital isolated Essex within hours"], c:3,
   e:"The rising collapsed because ordinary Londoners stayed loyal and the Privy Council swiftly proclaimed Essex a traitor, leaving him stranded with a couple of hundred men. His grievances were real enough — they explain why he rebelled, not why he failed."}
]);

QUESTIONS["h10i-03-2"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-03-2"] || []).concat([
  {q:"What was the aim of the Revolt of the Northern Earls in 1569?", opts:["To restore Catholicism and place Mary Queen of Scots on the throne","To demand a fully Puritan church settlement","To lower taxation in the northern counties","To make the Earl of Essex king"], c:0,
   e:"The Earls of Northumberland and Westmorland wanted Catholic worship restored and planned for Mary to marry the Duke of Norfolk and take the crown; Mass was even held in Durham Cathedral. It was a Catholic rising — the Puritan challenge came from the opposite religious direction."},
  {q:"What was planned in the Ridolfi Plot of 1571?", opts:["A Puritan march on London","A Spanish-backed rising in which Mary Queen of Scots would marry the Duke of Norfolk and replace Elizabeth","The kidnapping of Elizabeth during a royal progress","An attack on Drake's fleet at Plymouth"], c:1,
   e:"Roberto Ridolfi, an Italian banker, organised a conspiracy for a foreign-supported rising to put Mary on the throne as Norfolk's wife; Norfolk was executed in 1572. The plot was aimed at the Crown itself, not at the navy."},
  {q:"Who was Edmund Campion?", opts:["A Puritan MP imprisoned for demanding free speech","Elizabeth's ambassador in Rome","A Jesuit priest who secretly ministered to English Catholics and was executed in 1581","The architect of Hardwick Hall"], c:2,
   e:"Campion arrived with the first Jesuit mission in 1580, moved in disguise between Catholic households, and was captured, tortured and executed for treason in 1581. The imprisoned free-speech MP was Peter Wentworth — a Puritan, from the opposite end of the religious spectrum."},
  {q:"What was the purpose of the college founded at Douai by William Allen?", opts:["To train English Protestant bishops","To educate the sons of Elizabeth's courtiers","To print copies of the Book of Common Prayer","To train English Catholic priests to return secretly and keep the old faith alive"], c:3,
   e:"Allen's seminary, founded in 1568, trained missionary priests who began slipping back into England from 1574. It worked against the Religious Settlement, so the Protestant options invert its whole purpose."},
  {q:"Why did some Catholic gentry families build priest holes in their houses?", opts:["To hide visiting priests from government searchers, since sheltering a priest could mean death","To store unpaid recusancy fines","To protect valuables from vagrants","To conceal banned Puritan pamphlets"], c:0,
   e:"After the 1585 act made harbouring a priest a capital offence, ingenious hiding places — many built by Nicholas Owen — could save both the priest and the household during a search. They were built to conceal people, not money or print."},
  {q:"How did Walsingham obtain the evidence that condemned Mary Queen of Scots?", opts:["Mary confessed openly at her trial","Philip II of Spain handed over her correspondence","Spanish prisoners betrayed her after Gravelines","His agents intercepted her coded letters, smuggled in beer barrels, and his cipher expert decoded them"], c:3,
   e:"Walsingham secretly controlled the channel Mary believed was safe: every letter hidden in the beer barrels was copied and decoded by Thomas Phelippes, proving she approved Babington's plan. Mary denied the charges at her trial, so a confession is the false but tempting option."},
  {q:"How did Archbishop Whitgift deal with the Puritan challenge from 1583?", opts:["He abolished bishops to satisfy Puritan demands","He required all clergy to accept the Prayer Book and royal supremacy, removing those who refused","He invited the Pope to mediate the dispute","He ordered the closure of every London theatre"], c:1,
   e:"Whitgift's articles forced clergy to subscribe to the worship and structure of the established Church, and those who would not conform lost their livings. Far from abolishing bishops, his whole campaign defended them against Puritan attack."},
  {q:"What does the vestment controversy of the 1560s reveal about Elizabeth's approach to the Church?", opts:["She allowed each parish to choose its own forms of worship","She secretly preferred Catholic ceremonies","She insisted on outward uniformity, and clergy who refused to wear the surplice lost their posts","She handed control of worship over to Parliament"], c:2,
   e:"When some Protestant ministers rejected vestments as too Catholic, Elizabeth backed Archbishop Parker's rules and around 37 London clergy were deprived of their positions. The episode shows she would not tolerate variety in worship even from fellow Protestants — local choice was exactly what she refused."},
  {q:"Why do many historians see Mary Queen of Scots' arrival in England in 1568 as a turning point for the Catholic threat?", opts:["It immediately triggered a war with Scotland","It brought Catholic plotting to an end","It persuaded Philip II to abandon his invasion plans","It gave every later conspiracy a living figurehead with a strong claim, held inside England itself"], c:3,
   e:"Once Mary was in English custody, plotters from the Northern Earls to Babington had an obvious Catholic replacement for Elizabeth close at hand, which is why plots multiplied for nearly twenty years. Far from ending conspiracy, her presence generated it — the second option states the exact opposite of what happened."},
  {q:"An interpretation argues that the Religious Settlement of 1559 'satisfied nobody'. Which point most weakens this claim?", opts:["The great majority outwardly conformed and the Settlement survived the whole reign","Every Catholic refused to attend church from 1559 onwards","The Settlement was formally abandoned in 1570","Puritans accepted the Settlement without any complaint"], c:0,
   e:"Most people, including 'church papists' who privately kept Catholic sympathies, attended their parish church, and the Settlement endured for over forty years — strong evidence it was broadly workable. The other statements are simply untrue: many Catholics did attend, the Settlement was never abandoned, and Puritans complained loudly."}
]);

QUESTIONS["h10i-03-3"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-03-3"] || []).concat([
  {q:"What were John Hawkins' voyages of the 1560s known for?", opts:["Discovering a northern route to China","Carrying enslaved Africans across the Atlantic to sell in the Spanish colonies","Mapping the coastline of Australia","Defending Calais against the French"], c:1,
   e:"From 1562 Hawkins made three voyages transporting enslaved Africans to Spanish America, beginning English involvement in the transatlantic slave trade; the last ended in a Spanish ambush at San Juan de Ulua in 1568. He sought profit in the Atlantic, not a passage to Asia."},
  {q:"Where was Drake knighted in 1581, and why was this provocative?", opts:["At Westminster Abbey, because it broke church custom","In Plymouth, because the town sympathised with Spain","Aboard the Golden Hind at Deptford, because it publicly honoured a man Spain regarded as a pirate","In Cadiz, because the ceremony took place on Spanish soil"], c:2,
   e:"Elizabeth arranged the knighthood on Drake's own ship after his circumnavigation, deliberately celebrating raids that Spain considered straightforward piracy. Holding the ceremony on the Golden Hind made the insult unmistakable — it certainly did not happen in Spain."},
  {q:"What was 'Nova Albion'?", opts:["The stretch of Pacific coast in North America that Drake claimed for Elizabeth","Raleigh's original name for the Roanoke colony","A Spanish fortress in the Netherlands","The flagship of the Spanish Armada"], c:0,
   e:"During his circumnavigation Drake landed on the Pacific coast of North America and claimed the territory as Nova Albion. Raleigh's colonial region was named Virginia in honour of the Queen, which is the most tempting mix-up."},
  {q:"Which organisation, founded in 1600, signalled England's growing trading ambitions?", opts:["The Royal Society","The Bank of England","The Globe playing company","The East India Company"], c:3,
   e:"The East India Company received its royal charter at the end of 1600 to trade with Asia, using the joint-stock model to spread investors' risk. The Globe, opened in 1599, was a theatre — a cultural landmark, not a trading venture."},
  {q:"Which development made long ocean voyages more practical in the Elizabethan period?", opts:["Steam-powered engines","Better instruments such as the astrolabe, together with more accurate printed charts","Signal flags that could reach across the Atlantic","Canals linking England directly to Europe"], c:1,
   e:"Instruments like the astrolabe and quadrant let sailors estimate latitude, while printed maps using Mercator's 1569 projection improved course-plotting. Steam power is the anachronistic trap — it belongs to a period more than two centuries later."},
  {q:"Who were the 'groundlings' at an Elizabethan playhouse?", opts:["Actors who performed at ground level","Gardeners who maintained the playhouse yard","Musicians seated beneath the stage","Spectators who paid a penny to stand in the open yard around the stage"], c:3,
   e:"Groundlings stood in the pit for the cheapest admission of a penny, exposed to the weather while wealthier patrons sat under cover. They were audience members, not performers — the name comes from where they stood, not what they did."},
  {q:"Which playwright, author of Doctor Faustus, rivalled Shakespeare before dying violently in 1593?", opts:["Ben Jonson","Thomas Harman","Christopher Marlowe","Edmund Campion"], c:2,
   e:"Marlowe wrote Doctor Faustus and Tamburlaine and was killed in a Deptford lodging house in 1593. Ben Jonson was also a celebrated playwright, which makes him tempting, but he long outlived both Marlowe and Shakespeare."},
  {q:"Why were London's playhouses built in districts such as Southwark and Shoreditch?", opts:["Land in those districts was given away free","Those areas lay outside the City authorities' control, and the City feared disorder, plague and idleness","Audiences refused to enter the City walls","Elizabeth had banned performances inside London"], c:1,
   e:"The City corporation, influenced by Puritan hostility, restricted playing within its jurisdiction, so theatre owners built just beyond its boundaries. Elizabeth herself enjoyed plays at court and protected the companies, so a royal ban is the reverse of the truth."},
  {q:"What was the strongest motive behind most Elizabethan voyages of exploration?", opts:["Profit from trade, plunder and new markets","A wish to spread Puritanism overseas","Direct orders from the Pope","Pure scientific curiosity"], c:0,
   e:"Investors and the Crown backed voyages chiefly for financial return — Drake's circumnavigation repaid its backers spectacularly and Elizabeth herself profited. Curiosity and religion played their part, but it was the prospect of profit that actually attracted the capital."},
  {q:"At the time, why was Drake's circumnavigation judged a greater success than Raleigh's Virginia ventures?", opts:["Drake founded a permanent American colony","Roanoke produced more treasure than Drake's voyage","Drake's voyage returned vast treasure and prestige, while the Roanoke colony failed and vanished","Raleigh's ventures never received royal backing"], c:2,
   e:"The circumnavigation brought home plunder worth around £600,000 and humiliated Spain, whereas the Roanoke settlers disappeared and the colony returned no profit. Drake founded no colony at all — his success was measured in treasure and reputation, which is why the first option fails."}
]);

QUESTIONS["h10i-03-4"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-03-4"] || []).concat([
  {q:"What did the Statute of Artificers of 1563 require?", opts:["The closure of all almshouses","Free food for every parish in England","The branding of all beggars","Seven-year apprenticeships for craftsmen, with wage levels set by Justices of the Peace"], c:3,
   e:"The statute aimed to keep people in stable, skilled employment through long apprenticeships and locally fixed wages. Branding belonged to the harsh vagrancy laws against the wandering poor, not to this employment statute."},
  {q:"What did the 1576 Act for the Relief of the Poor introduce?", opts:["Stocks of raw materials such as wool so the able-bodied poor could work, plus houses of correction for those who refused","The very first poor rate in England","A complete ban on begging licences","Pensions for retired soldiers"], c:0,
   e:"The 1576 Act made towns provide materials so the unemployed could earn, with a house of correction in each county for the work-shy. Compulsory contributions towards poor relief had already developed under earlier laws, so 'first poor rate' is the trap."},
  {q:"Which officials were created by the 1597 Act for the Relief of the Poor?", opts:["Royal almoners","Overseers of the poor in every parish, who collected the rate and organised relief","Masters of the Revels","County sheriffs"], c:1,
   e:"The 1597 Act required each parish to appoint overseers of the poor to manage the poor rate, relieve the impotent and set the able-bodied to work — arrangements confirmed in 1601. Sheriffs already existed and dealt with law enforcement, not parish relief."},
  {q:"What was Bridewell in London used for during the Elizabethan period?", opts:["A royal residence for Elizabeth's court","A playhouse for the Lord Chamberlain's Men","A house of correction where vagrants were set to forced work","A college for training clergy"], c:2,
   e:"The former royal palace of Bridewell became a house of correction for vagrants and petty offenders, and its name became a general term for such institutions. It had indeed once been a palace, which makes the royal residence answer tempting but a generation out of date."},
  {q:"How did the town of Ipswich respond to poverty in 1569?", opts:["It expelled every poor person from the town","It introduced licences for beggars and opened a hospital that cared for the poor and trained children","It abolished its local poor rate","It built England's first purpose-built theatre"], c:1,
   e:"Ipswich pioneered organised local action with begging licences, a hospital and training for the young — the kind of scheme that later shaped national law. Simple expulsion was the older, cruder response that such schemes were designed to move beyond."},
  {q:"In Elizabethan pamphlets about rogues, what was an 'Abraham man'?", opts:["A licensed parish beggar wearing an official badge","An overseer of the poor","A trickster who pretended to be mad in order to win charity","A priest travelling in disguise"], c:2,
   e:"Pamphleteers catalogued types of fraudulent beggar, including the Abraham man, whose act of feigned madness was meant to unlock sympathy and alms. Licensed beggars were legal and badge-wearing — the Abraham man's entire method was deception."},
  {q:"Why did the mid-1590s see a peak in poverty and unrest?", opts:["A run of disastrous harvests drove food prices sharply upward while war taxation continued","The Poor Law of 1601 had just been repealed","Enclosure had been suddenly banned","England's population fell dramatically"], c:0,
   e:"Four failed harvests between 1594 and 1597 brought dearth, food riots and famine deaths in parts of the north, all while the Spanish war drained resources. The 1601 Poor Law came after this crisis — partly because of it — so it could not have been repealed beforehand."},
  {q:"Which underlying cause connects most other explanations of rising Elizabethan poverty?", opts:["The dissolution of the monasteries","Population growth, which intensified pressure on jobs, food prices and housing","The defeat of the Spanish Armada","The building of the London playhouses"], c:1,
   e:"A population rising towards four million increased demand for food and work, magnifying the effects of enclosure, inflation and bad harvests alike. The dissolution mattered, but it was a one-off loss of charity decades earlier rather than the continuing pressure behind the whole problem."},
  {q:"Why was the Elizabethan government so concerned about poverty?", opts:["It feared that hungry, masterless people might riot or rebel, threatening the social order","It wished to abolish the social hierarchy","Parliament forced a reluctant Queen to act","The Pope had demanded action"], c:0,
   e:"Anxiety about disorder runs through the legislation: vagrants were seen as a threat to the Great Chain of Being, and the food riots of the 1590s sharpened official alarm. Genuine charity existed too, but the state's driving concern was stability — certainly not any desire to level society."},
  {q:"An interpretation claims the 1601 Poor Law was 'purely an instrument of punishment'. How convincing is this?", opts:["Entirely convincing — the law contained no relief at all","Not convincing in any way — the law contained no punishments","Convincing only for the deserving poor","Only partly convincing — it punished those who refused work, but it also guaranteed organised relief for the old, sick and disabled"], c:3,
   e:"The 1601 law combined houses of correction for the work-shy with a compulsory rate funding genuine relief for the impotent poor, so both faces must be weighed. Claiming it contained no relief, or no punishment, ignores half the evidence in each direction."}
]);

QUESTIONS["h10i-03-5"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-03-5"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Why was the Duke of Medina Sidonia a questionable choice to command the Armada?", opts:["He was secretly a Protestant","He was an able administrator but had never commanded a fleet at sea","He refused to leave Spanish waters","He was English by birth"], c:1,
   e:"Medina Sidonia took over after the veteran admiral Santa Cruz died in February 1588; he was a capable organiser but admitted his lack of sea experience and even suffered seasickness. There is no evidence whatever that he was disloyal to Catholic Spain."},
  {q:"Why did the Armada sail in a crescent formation?", opts:["It let the fastest ships escape quickly if attacked","It was the traditional formation for entering harbour","The strongest warships on the tips could shield the slower supply and troop ships in the centre","It made the fleet harder to see from the English coast"], c:2,
   e:"The crescent was a disciplined defensive screen: any English thrust at the vulnerable centre risked being enveloped by the armed wings. Its purpose was protection of the convoy, not speed or concealment."},
  {q:"Who commanded the English fleet against the Armada?", opts:["Lord Howard of Effingham, with Drake serving as his vice-admiral","Sir Francis Drake alone","Sir Walter Raleigh","The Earl of Essex"], c:0,
   e:"Overall command lay with Lord Howard of Effingham, with Drake as his deputy. Drake's fame leads many students to assume he was in charge, but he ranked second."},
  {q:"How was news of the Armada's approach spread along the English coast?", opts:["Through printed newsletters","By carrier pigeons sent from Spain","By a prepared chain of hilltop beacons lit in succession","By the ringing of church bells in London first"], c:2,
   e:"Once the Armada was sighted off Cornwall, the beacon chain flashed the warning along the south coast within hours. Printed news circulated in the period but was far too slow to serve as an invasion alarm."},
  {q:"How had John Hawkins improved the English fleet before 1588?", opts:["He doubled the number of soldiers carried aboard each ship","He developed lower, faster 'race-built' galleons designed for long-range gunnery","He copied Spanish ship designs exactly","He fitted English warships with iron armour plating"], c:1,
   e:"As treasurer of the navy, Hawkins promoted sleeker galleons that sailed closer to the wind and fought with long-range culverins rather than by boarding. Cramming ships with soldiers was the Spanish approach — exactly what the English design rejected."},
  {q:"What was the significance of Elizabeth's appearance at Tilbury in August 1588?", opts:["It announced the signing of peace with Spain","It ordered the English fleet to stand down","It persuaded the Duke of Parma to abandon his invasion","Speaking before her troops, she answered doubts about female rule by claiming 'the heart and stomach of a king'"], c:3,
   e:"The Tilbury speech became a propaganda triumph, turning Elizabeth's gender from an apparent weakness into a rallying point. Peace with Spain did not come until 1604 — sixteen years later and after her death — so the first option fails on chronology."},
  {q:"What happened to much of the Armada on its voyage home?", opts:["Storms wrecked many ships on the Scottish and Irish coasts, and only around half the fleet reached Spain","It captured Ireland for Philip II","It regrouped and mounted a second attack on London","It surrendered to Drake at Plymouth"], c:0,
   e:"Forced to flee north around Britain, the battered fleet ran into Atlantic gales; thousands of sailors drowned or were killed when wrecked on the Irish shore. The Armada never mounted a second attack — it was struggling simply to get home."},
  {q:"What does the failure of the English counter-armada of 1589 suggest about the war with Spain?", opts:["That Spain had no navy left after 1588","That the 1588 victory had ended the fighting for good","That the Armada's defeat had not broken Spanish power, and the war would drag on until 1604","That Drake had changed sides"], c:2,
   e:"The expedition under Drake and Norris against Portugal lost thousands of men and achieved little, proving Spain remained formidable. Treating 1588 as the decisive end of the war is the classic oversimplification this episode corrects."},
  {q:"Why do many historians argue the Spanish plan was flawed even before the fireships attacked?", opts:["The Armada carried hardly any guns","Philip II had refused to fund the campaign properly","Medina Sidonia secretly intended to invade Scotland instead","There was no deep-water port where the fleet could safely join Parma's army, so the two halves of the invasion could never combine"], c:3,
   e:"The whole strategy depended on escorting Parma's barges across the Channel, yet no suitable harbour existed and messages between the two commanders took days. The Armada was in fact heavily armed — its guns were not the core weakness, the impossible rendezvous was."},
  {q:"An interpretation credits the Armada's defeat entirely to the 'Protestant Wind'. What is the strongest argument against it?", opts:["The weather stayed calm throughout 1588","The Armada had already been scattered at Calais and mauled at Gravelines before the storms struck","The Spanish fleet never actually entered the Channel","English ships took no part in any fighting"], c:1,
   e:"The storms destroyed ships that were already beaten and fleeing northwards after the fireships and Gravelines, so English action came first in the chain of causes. Claiming the weather was calm is simply false — the storms were real, just not the whole explanation."}
]);

QUESTIONS["h10i-03-6"] = (QUESTIONS["h10i-03-6"] || []).concat([
  {q:"Who designed Hardwick Hall?", opts:["William Shakespeare","Robert Smythson, one of the first people in England recognisable as an architect","Bess of Hardwick's first husband","Inigo Jones"], c:1,
   e:"Smythson, who had earlier worked at Longleat and Wollaton, gave Hardwick its symmetry and towers, showing that great houses were now professionally designed showpieces. Inigo Jones is the tempting wrong answer, but he belongs to the next, Stuart, generation."},
  {q:"How did Bess of Hardwick acquire the fortune that built Hardwick Hall?", opts:["She inherited it directly from Elizabeth I","Through privateering in the Caribbean","Through four advantageous marriages, each adding to her wealth and lands","From shares in the East India Company"], c:2,
   e:"Born into minor Derbyshire gentry, Bess rose through marriage — finally to the Earl of Shrewsbury — to become one of the richest women in England. The Queen rewarded courtiers with offices and favour, but she did not bequeath Bess a fortune."},
  {q:"What does the absence of moats, battlements and thick defensive walls at Elizabethan great houses indicate?", opts:["Their owners could not afford such defences","Building stone had become scarce in England","Parliament had outlawed fortified houses","That England was internally stable, so elites competed through display and comfort rather than military strength"], c:3,
   e:"Houses such as Hardwick face outward with vast windows, confident that private warfare was over under strong Tudor government. Cost was no barrier — these owners spent fortunes — they simply chose glass and symmetry over gun-loops."},
  {q:"Why was the High Great Chamber at Hardwick placed on the top floor?", opts:["Height signalled status — the most honoured guests climbed to the grandest rooms at the summit of the house","To keep the room warm in winter","To conceal it from ordinary visitors","Because the lower floors were prone to flooding"], c:0,
   e:"Hardwick ascends in status floor by floor, from services below to state rooms above, so a visitor literally climbed through the household's hierarchy. Top-floor rooms were actually harder to heat — comfort was deliberately sacrificed to ceremony."},
  {q:"The plaster frieze in Hardwick's High Great Chamber depicts the goddess Diana. Why was this subject chosen?", opts:["Diana was Bess of Hardwick's patron saint","It was the cheapest decorative scheme available","Diana, the virgin huntress, flattered Elizabeth I, the Virgin Queen, in the room built to receive her","Smythson selected it without consulting Bess"], c:2,
   e:"Associating the state room with Diana was a calculated compliment to the unmarried Queen, whom Bess hoped to honour and perhaps host. Diana is a classical goddess, not a saint — the choice reflects Renaissance learning rather than piety."},
  {q:"Why were tapestries so prominent at Hardwick Hall?", opts:["They were enormously expensive imports that proclaimed wealth, and some rooms were proportioned to display them","They deterred burglars","Great houses were legally required to display them","They were woven by the parish poor as relief work"], c:0,
   e:"Bess bought sets of Flemish tapestries before the house was even finished, and rooms were sized to show them off — fine textiles could cost more than the building work itself. No law required them; they were pure status display."},
  {q:"What can historians learn from Hardwick Hall's position on a hilltop ridge?", opts:["The site was chosen for defence against Scottish raids","The house was deliberately hidden from travellers","The hilltop offered the only flat building land in the county","It was built to be seen for miles, advertising Bess's wealth and dynastic ambition"], c:3,
   e:"Crowned with Bess's initials 'ES' against the skyline, the house was designed to dominate the landscape and proclaim its owner to everyone who passed. Defence is the tempting wrong answer — walls of glass would be useless in any siege."},
  {q:"Why did performances at the Globe take place in the afternoon?", opts:["The open-air playhouse depended on daylight, since there was no effective artificial lighting","The law required actors to work other trades each morning","Evening performances were reserved for the Queen alone","Afternoon admission prices were fixed by statute"], c:0,
   e:"The 'wooden O' was open to the sky, so plays needed natural light, with a flag and trumpet announcing each afternoon's show. This is a case where the building's physical form explains the rhythm of playgoing — no statute governed performance times in that way."},
  {q:"Why should a site study combine a building's physical evidence with written sources?", opts:["Written sources are always more reliable than buildings","Buildings reveal design and intention, while documents such as inventories reveal how rooms were actually furnished and used","Physical evidence is not credited in the examination","Buildings never change after construction"], c:1,
   e:"Hardwick's 1601 inventory records the contents room by room, adding detail the stones alone cannot supply, while the fabric shows priorities such as light, height and symmetry. Neither type of evidence is automatically superior — each answers questions the other cannot."},
  {q:"A student claims Hardwick Hall was built 'mainly to attract a visit from Elizabeth I'. What is the strongest qualification to this claim?", opts:["Elizabeth never travelled outside London","Royal visits to Derbyshire were forbidden","The Queen never came, and the house equally served Bess's lasting aims of dynastic status and display","The house contained no rooms fit for guests"], c:2,
   e:"The state rooms were certainly fit to receive a queen, but Elizabeth never visited Hardwick, and the rooftop initials, portraits and sheer scale point to Bess building for her family's permanent standing. Elizabeth's progresses did leave London — they simply rarely reached so far north — so the first option overstates the case."}
]);
